1 Verify no significant difference in sequencing depth per group

We wish to attribute any changes observed between samples to the donor group. It is therefore important to rule out differences in sequencing depth (number of sequences obtained per experimental group) as a potential confounding factor. The box plot and permanova confirm sequencing depth cannot be attributed to donor group.

# =================
# Check that sampling depth (number of OTU reads recorded for each sample) does not differ between groups
Num_Reads = colSums(otu_table(phylo_post))
Sample = sample_data(phylo_post)$Sample
Donor = sample_data(phylo_post)$Donor
sample_depth_df = data.frame(Sample, Donor, Num_Reads)

p = ggplot(sample_depth_df, aes(x=Donor, y=Num_Reads, color=Donor))
p + geom_boxplot(outlier.size=NA) +  # Turn off outliers, as we plot each datapoint below. 
  geom_jitter(shape=16, position=position_jitter(0.3), size=4)

ggsave("post_gavage_sampling_depth_Donor.pdf")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image
# Check significance. 
# Adonis is a stochastic algorithm.
# Ensure consistent results. I've checked multiple different seeds, result is consistently statistically insignificant. 
set.seed(999)
adonis(Num_Reads ~ Donor, data=sample_depth_df, method="euclidean")  # performs a permanova.

2 Sequencing depth was sufficient to identify all major taxa present

Another potential confounding factor is if the sequencing depth was not a sufficient sampling of all microbes in the environment. If we did not sequence deep enough, then it is possible that observed differences between groups could stem from not observing microbes that were in fact present had we only looked deeper. We test this by sub-sampling each sample and counting how the number of unique taxa identified grows with the number of sequences identified. We hope to observe a plateau, through which we can argue that further sampling would not have yielded any previously unobserved microbes.

We find that each sample achieves a plateau.

# =================
# Rarefaction curves. Check that we aren't sub-sampling to the point of missing OTUs/sequences. 
source('../microbial_ecology_tools/ggrare.R')
ggrare(phylo_post, step = 1000, label='Sample', color='Donor', plot = TRUE, parallel = TRUE, se = TRUE)

ggsave("post_gavage_rarefaction_curves.pdf")  # Would prefer to save as SVG, but can't get it working. 
## Saving 7 x 5 in image
# Change the order of samples to group by Donor. 
sd = sample_data(phylo_post)
sorted_sd = sd[order(sd$SortOrder), ]  # Ordered by SortOrder
desired_col_order = rownames(sorted_sd)  

# Plot richness
p = plot_richness(phylo_post, measures=c("Observed","Shannon","InvSimpson"), color="Donor")
# Change the order of the samples on the x axis to be listed by experimental group. This was manually determined in the mapping file: "SortOrder"
p$data$samples = as.character(p$data$samples)  # "Sample" here is data-set specific. It's the dataframe column being plotted on X
p$data$samples = factor(p$data$samples, levels=desired_col_order)
p + geom_point(size=2)

ggsave("post_gavage_alpha_diversity.pdf", width=15, height=7)  # Adjust the width of the saved plot, stop sample IDs being squeezed.
